WHAT IS THE PDA?

The patent pending PDA-Personal Defense Accessory holster addresses the inherent disadvantages of other concealed carry strategies.

Anything that reveals the shape or any part of the weapon must be covered from view, usually with a coat or shirttail. Cases or bags provide access with a zipper or other closure, causing the user to have to “make ready” by getting the case open. The trigger may be exposed inside the bag increasing the possibility of an accidental discharge when making the draw. Other carry choices must be worn inside or underneath clothing that has to be removed or disengaged to get into action. Any of these concealed carry methods can be uncomfortable, slow, or unsafe. Some are all three. The PDA is quick, safe, and comfortable. Our users tell us the time to first shot is as fast as from a thumb break holster, typically under 1.5 seconds. Tuck your shirttail in, take your jacket off or wear shorts when it’s hot. Carry heat and still be cool. PDA-Personal Defense Accessory.

title: For Sale:  BUYER BEWARE MUST READ!!!!!!!
postcontent:
So this had to be told it is the best example of checking real good before you buy a used firearm at a FFL. Looked at a Hi Power found its safety to not work allowing the hammer to fall and hit the firing pin while on safe I brought it  to the owners attention who dismissed it as normal operation and took it out back for "work" found it out in the case the next day still with a broken safety at the same price with no cautionary note guess they don't mind a serious safety issue so again I made then aware and its out back again wouldnt trust a repair by them having to admitted to using YouTube for repair info a couple years ago. So looked at a reasonably priced Glock found a hairline fracture on the slide rail owner again quick to dismiss it put it back in the case wile saying "its a Glock its fine" although another employee confirmed the crack. Also the same day overheard "its got a broken ----- " (wish I heard what) followed by "I'll still make money" from the owner. As you can see these people could care less about your personal safety and would rather make a huge profit. So take the time bring a bore light, magnifying glasses and familiarize yourself with what your looking for so you too can spot the accident waiting to happen. Hope this helped because I'm probably goin to be banned from @#$%&%$#@#$% cause if they read this they know who wrote it. Oh and if you think thats all I have I could write for days and this is just one dealer!  Wish I took pictures to email to the BBB. Didn't want to mention the name but if any concerned buyers especially in the south shore/coast area have any questions please ask. Again look close some (most) will always put profit before people. Did however find a nice firearm with no obvious flaws but after their lack of concern could not bring myself to buy it not knowing what could be beneath its cosmetically good exterior and on top certain employes attitudes made me decide I would rather pay more elsewhere.

Enjoy the picture of a random cat climbing a fence

Would recommend Hunters Trading Post that do look at firearms before sale and have been told what was replaced on certain firearms before sale a little more pricey but never brought something home that needed parts or work.

 BCM KMR-10


Bravo Company’s KeyMod™ Rail, 10”


Manufactured from an exclusive blended aluminum and magnesium alloy, it weighs 30-40% less than aluminum with the same strength properties. Also featuring a proprietary patent pending mounting, indexing and lock up system that mitigates 12:00 rail movement under heat generated from the barrel nut.


Handguard alone weighs 4.1oz!

1.3” Inner Diameter

1.5” OUTSIDE flat to flat.
Handguard flares forward (towards muzzle end) at the 3 and 9 O'clock positions approximately 1/4"

The KMR’s propriety finish was originally developed for the Aerospace industry. It is a plasma deposition process which creates a stabilized ceramic-like surface coating with superior wear resistance when compared to anodize or even hard chrome. The stabilized nature of the coating means it has a higher corrosion resistance as well, due to the lack of ‘pores’ in the surface.


The KeyMod™ interface system was developed by Eric Kincel (now the Director of BCMs' product development team) to work in parallel with the current picatinny system. In many applications it will advance modularity past the current 1913 rail system.


The BCM KMR also allows for a larger range of modularity offering 4 different offset mounting positions between traditional 3,6,9, and 12:00 positions.


In the most basic of applications the KeyMod™ system allows for universal modularity between various manufacturers of accessories, and accessory rails. A big win for the trigger puller. As the industry advances the modular accessories will mount directly to the KeyMod™ instead of picatinny, allowing for a lighter, cleaner, and less bulky weapon system.

title: For Sale:  BCM KMR13 (KeyMod™ Free Float Handguard) (NEW)
postcontent:
YOU CAN BUY THIS HERE>BCM KMR13 (KeyMod™ Free Float Handguard) 

BCM KMR-13


Bravo Company’s KeyMod™ Rail, 13”


Manufactured from an exclusive blended aluminum and magnesium alloy, it weighs 30-40% less than aluminum with the same strength properties. Also featuring a proprietary patent pending mounting, indexing and lock up system that mitigates 12:00 rail movement under heat generated from the barrel nut.


Handguard alone weighs 5.5oz!

1.3” Inner Diameter

1.5” OUTSIDE flat to flat.
Handguard flares forward (towards muzzle end) at the 3 and 9 O'clock positions approximately 1/4"

The KMR’s propriety finish was originally developed for the Aerospace industry. It is a plasma deposition process which creates a stabilized ceramic-like surface coating with superior wear resistance when compared to anodize or even hard chrome. The stabilized nature of the coating means it has a higher corrosion resistance as well, due to the lack of ‘pores’ in the surface.


The KeyMod™ interface system was developed by Eric Kincel (now the Director of BCMs' product development team) to work in parallel with the current picatinny system. In many applications it will advance modularity past the current 1913 rail system.


The BCM KMR also allows for a larger range of modularity offering 4 different offset mounting positions between traditional 3,6,9, and 12:00 positions.


In the most basic of applications the KeyMod™ system allows for universal modularity between various manufacturers of accessories, and accessory rails. A big win for the trigger puller. As the industry advances the modular accessories will mount directly to the KeyMod™ instead of picatinny, allowing for a lighter, cleaner, and less bulky weapon system.
